                <head>252. Editorial Note</head>
                <p>On November 4, 1980, the U.S. elections were held and the Republican Presidential
                    candidate, Governor <persName corresp="#p_RR_1">Ronald Reagan</persName>,
                    overwhelmingly defeated the Democratic candidate, President <persName
                        corresp="#p_CJ_2">Jimmy Carter</persName>. <persName corresp="#p_RR_1"
                        >Reagan</persName> received 50.7 percent of the popular vote to <persName
                        corresp="#p_CJ_2">Carter</persName>’s 41 percent and won 489 electoral votes
                    to <persName corresp="#p_CJ_2">Carter</persName>’s 49. <persName
                        corresp="#p_RR_1">Reagan</persName> had been critical of <gloss
                        target="#t_SALT_1">SALT</gloss> during the campaign. On November 20, from
                    2:07 to 3:32 p.m. President <persName corresp="#p_CJ_2">Carter</persName> and
                    President-Elect <persName corresp="#p_RR_1">Reagan</persName> met in the Oval
                    Office of the White House. (Carter Library, Presidential Materials, President’s
                    Daily Diary) According to his memoirs, <persName corresp="#p_CJ_2"
                        >Carter</persName> “listed some of the advantages to our country of honoring
                    the terms of SALT II, pending its ratification, and of maintaining a strong
                    nonproliferation policy.” (<persName corresp="#p_CJ_2">Carter</persName>, <hi
                        rend="italic">Keeping Faith</hi>, page 577) The Treaty, however, was never
                    ratified by the Senate.</p>
